Modern democracies are often assumed to be self-sustaining. They are expected to absorb shocks, correct errors, and survive periods of poor leadership or political conflict through the ordinary operation of institutions and norms. History suggests otherwise. Democratic systems can weaken, deform, and collapse\'97not usually through sudden rupture, but through gradual erosion. Republican Rome decayed into empire. Athenian democracy dissolved into oligarchy. More recently, democratic governments in Hungary, Russia, Venezuela, and elsewhere have hollowed out from within as constraints on power were steadily relaxed or ignored.\
\
The United States is not exempt from this pattern. Over the past several decades, trust in government has declined, institutional norms have thinned, and the separation of powers has weakened. Courts have become increasingly politicized. Executive authority has expanded. Alliances that once anchored American influence have frayed. Elections continue, but confidence in their legitimacy has eroded. Each of these developments is often treated as an isolated concern, a partisan talking point, or a temporary deviation. Taken together, they suggest a democratic system under sustained strain.\
\
Historians and political theorists have documented these patterns in detail. What remains elusive is a way to track democratic decline as it unfolds. In the present moment, radically different claims are made about the condition of American democracy. One side insists it remains strong and resilient; the other warns that it is damaged and approaching failure. Approval ratings, polling data, and media narratives are cited as evidence by both camps. None of these measures is decisive. All are vulnerable to manipulation by the very forces they are meant to assess. The result is argument without resolution and alarm without clarity.\
\
This book begins from that problem. If democracy is weakening, how would we know? How much damage has been done, where has it occurred, and how reversible is it? Without a way to measure democratic condition, decline remains a matter of interpretation until it becomes irreversible fact. Observation alone is insufficient. What is needed is a framework capable of seeing democratic change as it accumulates\'97across institutions, rights, governance, and moral obligation.\
\
To meet that need, this book constructs a measuring system for democracy itself. Measurement without definition is noise; definition without principles is arbitrary. The analysis therefore begins with first principles: why government exists, why democracy was chosen as a form of self-rule, what it promises, what it requires, and what it must deliver to retain legitimacy. From those foundations, the book defines a comprehensive set of democratic indicators and translates them into a single, cumulative measure: the Democracy Clock. Noon represents a fully functioning democracy. Midnight represents the absence of democratic governance. Movement between them reflects accumulated structural and moral change over time. The clock does not predict collapse or assign blame; it records change.\
\
Part II applies this measure week by week to the first year of Donald Trump\'92s second term, treating it as a continuous case study of democratic stress and response. Each week identifies actions that moved American democracy toward repair or toward further degradation. A companion volume documents the underlying governmental actions in full. Together, they form a continuous public record of democratic time lost and regained.\
\
The purpose of this book is to make democratic condition visible. It records change as it occurs, measures its accumulation, and preserves the evidence on which those measurements rest. Without such a record, democratic failure is recognized only in retrospect, when correction becomes far more difficult\'97if possible at all.}